properties.description: Named after the nickname of businessman Francisco Yat-Tse. He was the owner of Wing Kee Shipping and was the first Comparadore of Banco Ultramarino of Macao. He was known as "Chico" by the local Portuguese community.

properties.company: Chartered Mercantile Bank of India, London and China
properties.description: Named after Hong Kong businessman Sir Boshan Wei Yuk. He served as the head compradore of Chartered Mercantile Bank of India, London and China, and a member of the Legislative Council. He chaired Tung Wah Hospital and co-founding the Po Leung Kuk.

Named after businessman Sir Robert Hotung. He was Head Compradore at Jardines and was a director of Hong Kong Land and a board member of Tung Wah Hospital. By the age of 35, he was believed to be the richest man in Hong Kong.

properties.company: Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company
properties.description: Named after Fat Hing Hong, founded by early settler and Chinese business pioneer Kwok A-Cheong. Initially a comprador for P&O, he led its shipwright and engineering department, and became Hong Kong's third-largest ratepayer by 1876.

Named after Scottish sea captain and merchant John Burd, who co-founded John Burd and Co., a merchant and mariner company in Canton, which moved to Hong Kong in 1842. He was appointed as the inaugural Danish consul in Hong Kong in 1845.

Named after Amercian merchant Silas Enoch Burrows, who founded a shipping business in New York, San Francisco, and Hong Kong. He was known for aiding shipwrecked mariners, including those from Sir John Franklin’s Arctic expedition.

Named after Shanghai-born Jewish businessman Edward Isaac Ezra. Amassing wealth through opium trade and real estate, he served as the managing director of Shanghai Hotels Ltd. and chairman of the Far Eastern Insurance Company.

Named after Hong Kong businessman Lee Hysan, involved in the early 1900s opium trade, refinery, and land development. He purchased Jardine's Hill, west of Causeway Bay, for HK$3.8 million, which became Lee Garden.
Named after the old Hong Kong Yacht Club site, originally the Victoria Regatta, which hosted its first race in 1849. The clubhouse moved to Kellett Island in 1938.
